metadata.name: Misty Mountains #2
metadata.description:
A mountain range scribbled on a scrap piece of paper.

The smudging drenches the mountains further back into a thick fog while creating a pixelated background.


Please note that there is no smudging in the preview as it requires a GPU, so the previews will look different.


Features:
Full/Wading/Waxing Moon
6 Color palettes including monochrome
Black (20% chance) or White  sheet of paper

There are further variables that will affect the style in which the mountains and fog are drawn which are dependent on the hash. The outcomes can vary quite a bit. Check the variations function to see the possible results.

Controls:
S - Save 2000x2000 image
Space - Pause/Unpause animation
Up/Down-Arrows - Increase/Decrease speed


Created on 2D Canvas in Vanilla Js.

metadata.name: RE/Posizioni #145
metadata.description:
Exactly one year ago I was minting my first fxhash project. 
“Posizioni” was a quick sketch of only 25 editions that I put together to test this new platform and to my great surprise, it was the start of an amazing journey in this space that still continues to amaze me every day. 

“RE/Posizioni” is an ideal continuation of my personal path that started one year ago: I decided to create an animated, glitchy, or even broken piece, something completely different from what I usually do as an artist and as a coder (and probably something I’m not very good at, forgive me for this :D ).
Even if this NFT crazy world is often uncertain, insecure, or unstable, we need to find a balance no matter how difficult, just as the lines in this artwork try to do.

Going out of my comfort zone, experimenting, or just having fun is what keeps this creative practice enjoyable for me, and it’s all that matters.

----

- Mouse click to pause the animation
- "s" key to download a png
- "f" key to full screen

Tested on Desktop/Chrome.
See LICENSE.md for more licensing details.

metadata.name: haphazard  #14
metadata.description:
'haphazard' by Happy Accidents 

Colourful, playful, happy.
Exploring the mash up of AI images & p5js.

27 image assets are included as possible textures. These assets were made with midjourney and are my own personal creations, I am also a paid subscriber with MJ.

Prompts ranged from inputing several lines of p5js code that would create a grid of rectangles (in p5js) to some more simple descriptive commands.

Thanks for collecting!
Click the image or press ‘s’ or ‘S’ in live mode to download png.


**reserves will be cleared after 7 days and remaining iterations open to public sale, if you have a reserve and cannot mint in that time please DM on twitter**

Made with p5js
© Happy Accidents, 2022

metadata.name: Flippr #73
metadata.description:
Experiments in 3D, moiré, monochrome and flipping planes.

Around 600.000 pixels, all black planes rotating on their own axis. 
The angle of rotation will define the contrast and create different images over time.

Zoom in and move around to explore each pixel and its movement in detail.

On some rare occasions the pixels are white and background is black.

December 2021, Berlin
by @bgola

metadata.name: Polytone #68
metadata.description:
A graphic poetry between order and chaos.

Voltaire, the philosopher, created the french word « Polytone » to define, in poetry, what is opposed to monotony. This generative work is an attempt to find it in a graphic poetry between order and chaos.

Format: 
Loop 400 frames - 50 FPS - 1000x1000px max. on screen.
By default the loop plays once then stops.

Controls with keyboard :
[p] -> play/pause animation (2 times when loop is off)
[l] -> on/off looping mode
[h] -> switch between 2 stop frames (when loop is off)
[s] -> Export HD capture (8000x8000px) when you want in the loop (only in « Open Live » mode)

Some features with probabilities:
2 colours background : Black (50%) or White (50%)
5 colours palettes : 2 monochrones (45%) or 2 duotones (30%) or 2 composed of 5 colours (25%)
6 pattern types for the image background (16.6% for all)
6 « noise » types : Crosses (26%) or Points (22%) or Line (18%) or Triangle (14%) or Circle (12%) or squad (8%) 
…

metadata.name: Bored Computer Screen #792
metadata.description:
"Bored Computer Screen" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022


Bored Computer Screen (BCS) is a direct descendant of Specter👻pixel⬛latte☕, where the central idea is agent and displacement. In BCS, there are agents—the small moving circles—that get their colors ripped away by the surrounding pixels. Though they occur on the same screen space, they are separated in their own cells, a simultaneous multiverse of sorts. In some iterations, a very clear voronoi pattern will appear. I didn't consciously strive for this look. It's what naturally happens, when you try to divide space, so that the borders occur exactly in between the closest neighbor. When I first saw this pattern emerge, I wanted to see how far I could get the distinct cells to influence each other. The idea that the same algorithmic processes can happen many times but still separately in a single piece has always interested me (and explored in the Infinite Browse series). BCS is an extension of that, albeit a little more chaotic.

Note:
- Best experience on browsers and devices with support for WebGL2 

Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with P5, P5Fbo and perlinjs.

attributes.name: A More Descriptive Number of Cells

metadata.name: rive #431
metadata.description:
Starting with a repeatable system of colors and/or triangles typically seen in geometric abstraction, rive employs generative art to break/split/rive those patterns–and the comfort we find in them–in slight, seemingly unintentional ways.  With each subsequent split, our comfort fades as the artwork is shredded into barely recognizable fragments of a once carefully orchestrated pattern.

Not all rivings are created equal; some are subtle and barely visible while others are acute and violent.  

What holds it together is what breaks it apart.  

created using triangles and p5js

rive
abstractment, 2022

___________________________

Functionality:
Press ‘p’ to save as a png.
Press 0-9 to render at varying degrees of quality. 0 to 9 (highest quality, ~15k x ~15k, depending on the dimensions).  The window background will change colors when completed rendering.
Press ⬆️ (arrow up) to increase pixel density by 0.5.
Press ⬇️ (arrow down) to decrease pixel density by 0.5.
